The paper deals with the analysis of non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) networks, which is a topic related to information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The focus on success probability and signal-to-interference ratio (SIR) coverage probability suggests a possible fit with the sub-category of stochastic processes (cs.SI). The optimization of power allocations for NOMA users also suggests a possible fit with the sub-category of multi-agent systems (cs.MA). Finally, the use of meta distribution and moments analysis suggests a possible fit with the sub-category of game theory (cs.GT).
